<problem>
<!-- <title>Applications of integration - average value</title> -->

<setup>


<function name='f' variables = 't' >t</function>
<function name='g' variables='t' symbolic>e^(2t)</function>
<math name='lb' >0</math>
<math name='ub' >3</math>
<function name='integral_g' variables = 't' symbolic >(1/2)e^(2t) </function>
<math name='ave_g' simplify='full' >$integral_g /($ub -$lb )</math>
<math name='average_g_evaluated' simplify='full'>($$integral_g($ub)-$$integral_g($lb))/($ub -$lb)</math>
<evaluate name="intg0" forceNumeric function="$integral_g" input="0" />
<evaluate name="intg3" forceNumeric function="$integral_g" input="3" />
<number name='numeric_ave_g_eval'>($intg3-$intg0)/($ub -$lb )</number>
<math name='integral_g_eval' simplify='full' >$$integral_g($ub)-$$integral_g($lb) </math>

  
<function name='h' variables='t' symbolic> 10t^2+20t+10</function>
<function name='integral_h' variables = 't' >(10/3)*t^3+10*t^2+10t</function>
<math name='ave_h' simplify='full' >$integral_h /14</math>
<math name='ave_h_eval' simplify='full' >($$integral_h(14))/14 </math>
<math name='integral_h_eval' >$$integral_h(14) </math>
<evaluate name='inth14' forceNumeric function="$integral_h" input="14" />
<number name="numeric_ave_h_eval">$inth14/14</number>
<evaluate name='sym_h_eval' function="$integral_h" forceSymbolic input='14' />
<math name='sym_ave_h_eval' simplify='full'>($sym_h_eval)/14</math>

</setup>

<p>
We can use definite integrals to help us find averages.</p>

<!--Problem #1*******************************************-->
<ol>

<li>
<p>Suppose we know that the volume of a cell is changing at a rate of <m>f(t)</m> <m>\mu {\rm m}^3/s</m> and we want to know the average rate from <m>t=a</m> to <m>t=b</m> seconds.  The average rate of change is given by 
<answer inline='true'>
<choiceinput>
<choice credit='1'>the total change divided by the time that has passed</choice>
<choice>the time that has passed divided by the total change</choice>
<choice>the total change times the time that has passed</choice>
</choiceinput>
</answer>
.  Since the total change is given by 
<answer inline='true'>
<choiceinput>
<choice credit='1'>the definite integral of f</choice>
<choice>the indefinite integral of f</choice>
<choice>the derivative of f</choice>
</choiceinput>
</answer>
 and the time that has passed is given by 

<answer name='diff1'>b-a</answer>

, we can write down a formula for the average rate of change:
</p>

<p><m>\displaystyle  \frac{1}{<copy prop="submittedResponse" tname="diff1" componentType="math" />}
\int_{ <copy prop="immediateValue" tname="a1" /> }^{ <copy prop="immediateValue" tname="b1" /> }</m>  
<mathinput name="u_f" />
 <m>dt</m>, where integration limits are from 
<mathinput name="a1" />
to 
<mathinput name="b1" />.
<answer name="ansAve1">
<award matchPartial targetsAreResponses="a1 b1">
  <when>($(u_f{prop='value' isResponse})=f(t) or $u_f=f) and <when>$a1=a and $b1=b</when>
</when></award>
</answer>
</p>



<p>For any function <m>f(t)</m>, the formula gives us the average value of <m>f(t)</m> between <m>t=a</m> and <m>t=b</m>.  Suppose we want to know the average volume of the cell between <m>t=a</m> and <m>t=b</m>, where the volume at time <m>t</m> is given by <m>F(t)</m>.  The formula for this is:
</p>

<p><mathinput name="ab2" />
<m>\displaystyle  \int_{ <copy prop="immediateValue" tname="a2" /> }^{ <copy prop="immediateValue" tname="b2" /> }</m>  
<mathinput name="u_F" />
 <m>dt</m>, where integration limits are from 
<mathinput name="a2" />
to 
<mathinput name="b2" />.
<answer name="ansAve2">
<award matchPartial targetsAreResponses="ab2 a2 b2">
  <when>$ab2 = 1/(b-a) and ($(u_F{prop='value' isResponse})=F(t) or $u_F=F) and <when>$a2=a and $b2=b</when>
</when></award>
</answer>
</p>


</li>


<!--Problem #2********************************************-->
<li>
<p>
Find the average value of the function <m>g(t)=<copy prop="formula" tname="g" /></m> between <m>t= $lb </m> and <m>t=$ub </m>.  First write down the expression involving an integral that will give the average value, then evaluate it.
</p>

<p>The integration limits are from <mathinput name="a3" />
to 
<mathinput name="b3" /> 
