<!--Problem#3*************************************************-->
<li>
<p>A disease is infecting people at a rate of <m><copy prop="formula" tname="h" /></m> people per day, where <m>t</m> gives time in days.  Write down an expression involving an integral that gives the average rate of infection over the first two weeks and evaluate it. 
</p>

<p>The integration limits are from <mathinput name="a4" />
to 
<mathinput name="b4" />.
<answer matchPartial nAwardsCredited="2">
  <award targetsAreResponses="a4 b4">
    <when>$a4=0 and $b4=14</when>
  </award>
  <award credit="0" name="weeks">
    <when>$b4=2</when>
  </award>
</answer>.</p>
<feedback condition="$weeks">Since <m>t</m> is in days, enter expression in terms of days, not weeks.
</feedback>
  
<p>Average value = <mathinput name="ab4" />
<m>\displaystyle  \int_{ <copy prop="immediateValue" tname="a4" /> }^{ <copy prop="immediateValue" tname="b4" /> }</m>  
<mathinput name="u_h" />
 <m>dt</m>
<answer name="ansAve4">
<award matchPartial targetsAreResponses="ab4 u_g">
  <when>$ab4 = 1/14 and $u_h=$h</when>
</award>
</answer>
</p>
  

<p>
<m> = </m> 
<answer>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare> $ave_h_eval </award>
<award  credit='0.9' name='award14' allowedErrorInNumbers='0.1'>$numeric_ave_h_eval </award>
<award symbolicEquality='true' simplifyOnCompare credit='0' name='award15'>$integral_h_eval </award>
</answer>
<feedback condition="$award14">For full credit, don't round your answer but leave it in terms of <c>e^()</c> and/or a fraction.</feedback>
<feedback condition="$award15">Don't forget to divide by the change in time.</feedback>
</p>

<hint>
Since the infection rate <m><copy prop="formula" tname="h" /></m> and time <m>t</m> are given in days, be sure to think in terms of days, not weeks.
</hint>
</li>

</ol>



  
<solution>
<ol>
<li>
<p>The average rate of change of a function is given by the total change divided by the total time that has passed.  We have seen how to find the total change by evaluating a definite integral, namely <m>\displaystyle \int_a^b f(t)dt</m>, and the total time that has passed is just <m>b-a</m>.  So the average rate of change is <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{b-a} \int_a^b f(t)dt</m>.</p>

<p>The average rate of change is the average of the function <m>f(t)</m>.  We can use the same formula to determine the average value of any function <m>F</m>: <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{b-a} \int_a^b F(t)\, dt</m> gives the average value of <m>F(t)</m> from <m>a</m> to <m>b</m>.</p>
</li>

<li>
The average value of the function <m>g(t)=<copy prop="formula" tname="g" /></m> between <m>t= $lb </m> and <m>t=$ub </m> is given by
<me>\frac{1}{ $ub -$lb  } \int_{$lb}^{$ub} $g dt =\frac{1}{ $ub -$lb } \displaystyle \left($integral_g \right) \Bigg|_0^3 = $average_g_evaluated </me>
</li>

<li>
The average rate of infection over the first two weeks is given by
<me>\frac{1}{14-0} \int_{0}^{14} $h dt =\frac{1}{14 - 0} \displaystyle \left($integral_h \right) \Bigg|_0^{14} = $sym_ave_h_eval </me>
  
</li>


</ol>

</solution>


</problem>